  <brief_title>PICO Above Incisions After Vascular Surgery</brief_title>
  <official_title>PICO Versus Standard Dressing Above Groin Incisions After Vascular Surgery - a Prospective Randomized Trial</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Skane University Hospital</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>Skane University Hospital</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The wound infection rate in the groin after vascular surgery has been denoted to be high
      since the wound surveillance register started in 2005. The current wound infection rate based
      on a validation study was 22.9% (24/105 patients with groin incision(s) between 1 March to 30
      June in 2012). The Deep/superficial infection ratio was 7/17. To prove that PICO (negative
      wound pressure therapy) reduces the wound infection rate with ½ standard deviation, 90% power
      at the 5% significance level, inclusion of 160 patients, 80 patients in the PICO Group and
      the standard dressing group are needed.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
